    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>PageRank</strong> is Google's original algorithm for measuring the importance of a webpage based on the number and quality of other pages linking to it. Developed by Larry Page and Sergey Brin at Stanford in 1998, it adapted academic citation analysis to the web. Google stopped showing public PageRank scores in 2016, but patent filings and engineer statements confirm evolved versions continue operating inside their ranking systems.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Created</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Stanford, 1998</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Off-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Damping factor</div>
            <div class="tms-value">0.85</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Advanced</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">PageRank is why backlinks matter. Every link from another page is a vote — but votes from high-authority pages count far more than votes from low-authority ones. Understanding PageRank explains why one link from a single high-authority source can outrank dozens of weak ones.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is PageRank?</h2>
        <p>PageRank treats the web as a citation graph. Each page starts with a base score and receives fractional authority from every page that links to it. A link from a page with high PageRank passes more authority than a link from a page with low PageRank. The key insight: not all links are equal.</p>
        <p>The original paper, "The PageRank Citation Ranking: Bringing Order to the Web" (Page et al., Stanford, 1998), described the algorithm as simulating a "random surfer" who clicks links indefinitely. The probability they land on any given page equals that page's PageRank.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Still active in 2026</div>
          <p>Google confirmed in 2017 patent filings that modified PageRank variants continue operating within their ranking systems. Backlinks remain a confirmed top-3 ranking factor. Public scores disappeared in 2016 to prevent manipulation, not because the underlying concept became less important.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why PageRank matters for SEO</h2>
        <p>PageRank is the mechanism behind why backlinks affect rankings. Four practical implications:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Not all links are equal.</strong> One link from a prestigious editorial source (major publication, university, government site) outweighs hundreds of directory submissions. Quality of linking domain matters more than raw link count.</li>
          <li><strong>Internal links distribute authority.</strong> Every internal link you add from a high-PageRank page to a priority page passes real authority. You can dramatically improve rankings for key pages by restructuring internal links — no external backlinks required.</li>
          <li><strong>Unreachable pages get no PageRank.</strong> Pages buried more than 3-4 clicks from the homepage receive minimal PageRank. Orphaned pages — those with no internal links — receive effectively zero.</li>
          <li><strong>Link dilution is real.</strong> A page with 50 outbound links passes far less authority per link than a page with 5 outbound links. The available PageRank is split equally among all outbound links.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How PageRank works — the mechanics</h2>
        <p>The PageRank formula has four core components:</p>

        <h3>1. The voting model</h3>
        <p>Each page votes for the pages it links to. The vote weight equals the linking page's PageRank divided by its total number of outbound links. A page with PageRank 100 and 10 outbound links passes 10 units per link. A page with PageRank 100 and 100 outbound links passes 1 unit per link.</p>

        <h3>2. The damping factor (0.85)</h3>
        <p>The random surfer doesn't follow links forever — they occasionally type a new URL directly. The damping factor (d = 0.85) models this. It prevents infinite concentration of PageRank on a single page and ensures even pages with no incoming links receive a baseline score.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Simplified PageRank formula</span><br>
          PR(A) = (1-d) + d * (PR(B)/C(B) + PR(C)/C(C) + ...)<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Where:</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># d = damping factor (0.85)</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># PR(B) = PageRank of linking page B</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># C(B) = number of outbound links from page B</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Iterative recalculation</h3>
        <p>PageRank cannot be calculated in a single pass — it requires iterative computation across the entire web graph until scores stabilise. Google recalculates continuously as new pages and links are discovered.</p>

        <h3>4. Topic-sensitive weighting</h3>
        <p>Modern PageRank variants weight links by topical relevance, not just raw authority. A backlink from a topically relevant source in the same industry passes more effective PageRank than an equal-authority link from an unrelated domain.</p>

        <h2 id="types">PageRank variants and third-party proxies</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Metric</th><th>Creator</th><th>Scope</th><th>Scale</th><th>Public access</th></tr>
            </thead>
