        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real PageRank examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Content cluster — internal PageRank without external backlinks</h3>
        <p>An HVAC services blog published 30 articles per month, interlinking all 180 articles over 6 months into a tight content cluster. Despite having few external backlinks, the internal PageRank distribution pushed category pages to page-1 rankings for competitive local keywords. Internal links did the job that external link building typically requires.</p>

        <h3>2. Single high-authority backlink — position 14 to 6 in 8 weeks</h3>
        <p>An accounting firm's service page sat at position 14 for "small business accountant [city]". A Forbes guest post mentioning and linking to the service page moved it to position 6 within 8 weeks. The Forbes domain passes significant PageRank — one link from a domain ranking for millions of terms outweighed dozens of directory links the firm had built over years.</p>

        <h3>3. Site architecture — orphaned page recovery</h3>
        <p>A real estate site had a high-quality neighbourhood guide indexed but stuck at position 23. Analysis revealed the page had only one internal link from a buried category page, 4 clicks from the homepage. Adding 12 contextual internal links from relevant blog posts and the homepage sidebar moved it to position 8 within 6 weeks. Content didn't change — only PageRank flow did.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">PageRank vs. Domain Authority — which one should you track?</h2>
        <p>This comparison matters because SEO tools show DA/DR constantly, but Google uses neither. Here is the practical distinction:</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>PageRank (what Google uses)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Per-page scoring — not domain-level</li>
              <li>Reflects actual Google ranking input</li>
              <li>Accounts for link equity dilution per outbound link</li>
              <li>Updated continuously as Google recrawls</li>
              <li>Not publicly accessible since 2016</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Domain Authority (third-party estimate)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Domain-level scoring — not per-page</li>
              <li>Moz's prediction of Google rankings, not Google's own signal</li>
              <li>Useful for comparing sites at a high level</li>
              <li>Manipulable through link schemes</li>
              <li>Not correlated with Google rankings as cleanly as PA/UR</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 PageRank best practices for 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Target high-authority pages, not just high-DA domains.</strong> A link from a top-ranking page on a mid-DA domain can pass more PageRank than a buried page on a high-DA domain. Check the linking page's URL Rating in Ahrefs, not just domain-level authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Flatten your site architecture.</strong> Keep every important page within 3 clicks of the homepage. Each additional click depth reduces the PageRank a page receives from your homepage's authority pool.</li>
          <li><strong>Link strategically from your highest-PageRank pages.</strong> Identify your top-authority pages (highest inbound links, oldest pages, most linked-to content). Add contextual internal links from those pages to your conversion or priority ranking pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Never add nofollow to internal links.</strong> Nofollow on internal links blocks PageRank flow to linked pages. Internal nofollow is rarely justified and typically represents a configuration error.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish content that earns links passively.</strong> Original data studies, comprehensive guides, free tools, and contrarian analysis attract editorial backlinks. Each editorial backlink passes real PageRank that you cannot replicate through internal linking alone.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — using Domain Authority as a proxy for PageRank</div>
          <p>DA is a domain-level metric. PageRank is a page-level metric. A domain with DA 80 can have individual pages with minimal PageRank if they have few internal or external links pointing to them. Always evaluate the specific page you want a link from, not just the domain it's on. Check Ahrefs URL Rating or Moz Page Authority for the page-level signal.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common PageRank mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Building links to the homepage only</strong> — PageRank built on the homepage must flow through internal links to reach product and category pages. Build links directly to the pages you want to rank.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring internal linking</strong> — internal links are free PageRank distribution. Most sites under-invest here while spending heavily on external link building.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing DA over page-level authority</strong> — a DA-90 domain's 500th blog post passes less PageRank than a DA-60 domain's heavily linked cornerstone piece.</li>
          <li><strong>Allowing redirect chains to absorb PageRank</strong> — each redirect hop in a chain leaks a fraction of link equity. Redirect directly to the final URL.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating all links as equal</strong> — 500 blog comment links pass less PageRank combined than a single editorial mention in a well-linked industry publication.</li>
          <li><strong>Removing pages without redirecting</strong> — deleted pages lose all earned PageRank. 301 redirect them to the closest relevant page to preserve equity.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is PageRank still used by Google?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Patent filings and Google engineer statements confirm evolved versions of PageRank remain operational within Google's ranking systems. Public scores disappeared in 2016 to reduce manipulation incentives, but the underlying link-authority concept continues to influence rankings.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I check my PageRank?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Real PageRank scores are not publicly accessible since Google retired Toolbar PageRank in 2016. Third-party estimates include Moz's Page Authority (PA) and Ahrefs' URL Rating (UR), which are the closest available proxies for page-level link authority.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do nofollow links pass PageRank?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Officially no. Since 2019, Google treats nofollow as a "hint" with possible rare application, but dofollow links reliably transmit PageRank. Nofollow links may provide referral traffic and brand signals but should not be counted in link equity calculations.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does internal linking affect PageRank?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Absolutely. Strategic internal linking distributes PageRank to priority pages across your site without requiring external backlinks. Pages deep in site architecture receive less PageRank from the homepage — flattening site depth is one of the most underused PageRank tactics.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What replaced Toolbar PageRank?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No direct Google replacement exists. Third-party tools — Moz's Page Authority, Ahrefs' URL Rating, and Semrush's Authority Score — serve as proxies. None are as authoritative as the original Toolbar PageRank since they estimate Google's internal score rather than measuring it directly.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

